  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Anne Warren Weston describes a social gathering, at the house of Ellis Gray Loring, to meet Mr. Turnbull, English abolitionist and friend of Harriet Martineau. &quot;There was so much champagne drunk as quite surprised me.&quot; Anne rejoiced over Deborah&apos;s letter: &quot;Well done, Bristol Board!&quot; John A. Collins and Wendell Phillips had success in Tauton, although &quot;Hopkins Emery opposed them at every step.&quot; Henry C. Wright, in a letter, said that the course of the Executive Committee at New York is much censured by [William] Goodell, [William] Lawrence Chaplin and especially Alvan Stewart. &quot;They think that N.Y. folks ought to be deprived of a portion of their power &amp; Alvan Stewart thinks that $10,000 a year is as much as they ought to receive from all the states together.&quot; Wendell Phillips has been very successful at Fall River. &quot;[Alanson] St. Clair has made it his business to abuse Maria at Fall River ... [Gilbert. H.] Durfee has threatened not to go to another A. S. [anti-slavery] meeting till there was a new organization.&quot; Anne recounts in detail the meeting of the Boston Female Anti-Slavery Society on Wednesday, April 10. &quot;We have lost all but our honour,&quot; as the vote was in favour of party approving a direct pledge to the American Anti-Slavery Society. &quot;We do not feel at all discouraged by our defeat but rejoice that our Fair will at least show a pure communion.&quot; Wendell Phillips &amp; John A. Collins had &quot;a very fine time&quot; at East Weymouth.</subfield>
